projectInfo.name: Refugee Site Mapping Ifo - Kenya
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Kenyan government in facing the challenges associated with this influx of refugees. Among other things, the UNHCR manages the establishment of refugee settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid.

UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map several camps that do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads.
projectInfo.description:
Ifo refugee camp is part of the Dadaab refugee complex. This complex has a population of 212,936 registered refugees and asylum seekers as at the end of August 2019. It consists of four camps : Dagahaley, Ifo, Ifo 2 and Hagadera
 
The first camp was established in 1991, when refugees fleeing the civil war in Somalia started to cross the border into Kenya. A second large influx occurred in 2011, when some 130,000 refugees arrived, fleeing drought and famine in southern Somalia. There is a considerable difference between the old camps, established 1991 and 1992, and the new camps, established in 2011. A large part of the residents in the old camps (Ifo, Dagahaley, Hagadera) arrived in Dadaab in the 1990s and have children and grandchildren born in the camps. 
 
The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Kenyan government in facing this influx of refugees. Among other things, it manages the establishment of settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid. 

UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map these camps, which do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads. CartONG has been working with UNHCR for several years on mapping and information management, helping them to map camps and carry out surveys that serve to improve the living conditions of refugees.

You can find an example of one way CartONG and UNHCR are using the data created by following on this link : 
https://unhcr.maps.arcgis.com/apps/Cascade/index.html?appid=5fe87e78a97842819f8888a43e52eafe
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Choice of aerial imagery ============ You will use **Maxar Premium Imagery (Beta)** imagery for this project. 2. Habitations ============ * **Be as precise as possible! !** _Zoom in to distinguish buildings. Trace each building as a whole even if it is partly covered by trees on the satellite image._ ##**How ?** *With the web editor ID:* 1. Use the **polygon** tool to trace buildings 2. Once the building has been plotted, go to the menu on the left, look for the category **"Building types"**, then at the top of the list, select **"Building"** (this is the generic type that we can use, because we can not know the more specific use of a building from the aerial imagery alone) 3. Finally, correct the right angles by pressing the **"Q" key** ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With the JOSM editor:* 1. Use the **Draw Nodes** tool to draw buildings or the **buildings_tools** plugin.   2. Trace the building and use the **building = yes** tag 3. Finally, if you use the Draw Nodes tool, remember to correct the angles by pressing the **"Q" key** `Warning: Many buildings are very close but in fact do not touch each other, try to draw them close to each other but without connecting them or sharing nodes with other buildings, roads or contours of residential areas. In the iD web editor, when you press the Alt key, you will prevent the nodes from sticking to each other or attaching themselves to a nearby path to accidentally connect to it.` --- 3. Road Network ============ * **Please plot the most clearly identifiable routes** * **Connect routes to the existing network** whenever is possible. * **Very short segments that do not connect to anything should not be mapped** * **Overflow slightly from your square** so that the person mapping to the next square can easily connect to it. **The classification of roads in developing countries is different from that of developed countries.** The appearance and practicability of roads in developing countries are not always representative of their economic and social role. In OSM, the typology of roads is based on the importance of roads and not on the state of their surface or their visual appearance. The typology proposed in OSM for developing countries is based on a mapping experience on several of these countries, as well as many conversations and discussions, it is more adapted to the context of these countries. ##**For this project we will use the following categories:** * **For roads that connect cities between them choose "Secondary Roads" then "Minor or Unclassified Road"** (highway=unclassified) * **Within a village or residential area use "Secondary Roads" then "Residential Road"** (highway=residential) * **Roads of - of 1m (= path) use "Paths" then "Path not drivable"** (highway=path) Only trace major paths that connect to inhabited places or other roads. ##**How ?** *With the web editor ID:* 1. Use the **line** tool to draw the routes 2. Once you have drawn a route, go to the left menu, find the category that corresponds to the typology of the route or path (see definition above) *With the JOSM editor:* 1. Use the **Draw Nodes** tool to trace roads and paths 2. Draw the route and then use the tag corresponding to the typology of it. **Highway = Unclassified** or **Highway = residential** or **Highway = path** (see definition above) --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain in the database OSM data and visible and reusable by all. Be as specific as possible! **Quality is more important than quantity! ** Remember that mapping requires patience, care and attention.

** If you have any questions, please post them in comment**, our volunteers xould be happy to answer !
